\n- cron:ed2d0b5d: running ✅\\n- cron:e7885813: running ✅\\n- cron:6f3323ef: running ✅\\n- cron:53c5832a: done ✅\\n- main: done ✅\\n- telegram:direct:6053576134: done (ended ~22:02 UTC)\\n- telegram:group:-5163901258: running ✅\\n\\n**Current (00:29 UTC):**\\nLooking at sessions_list output, the running sessions are:\\n1. \\n\\nSo comparing the two snapshots, I see three cron jobs still running and a new instance of telegram:direct:6053576134 that's been active for about 17 minutes, while the old one had ended. The other cron jobs haven't changed, and there's a new one I need to account for.\\n\\nLooking at what's actually changed since the last baseline, the main difference is that the Telegram direct session has restarted—it's now running again after being marked as ended at 22:02 UTC. Since this is a new instance with a different session ID, it's technically a state change from the previous report.\\n\\nThe DTLX cron appears stable and hasn't generated any new messages since the group session ended around 22:55 UTC. Comparing the full baseline from 00:14 UTC to now at 00:29 UTC, the same three cron jobs are still running, the QLHV session continues, and this new Telegram session has spun up. So yes, there's been a state change—the Telegram direct session restarted—but it's not necessarily significant for the DTLX pipeline.\\n\\nLooking at what matters for the DTLX context specifically: all the critical crons are running, there are no failures, and the DTLX group session ended 34 minutes ago. The new Telegram direct session is just a communication channel, not a pipeline component. The real question is whether the group session ending matters for DTLX operations, and based on the last report, that was already expected. Looking at the session list more carefully, the DTLX cron is the only active session for this pipeline right now, and checking back against the last status from 00:14 UTC, the Telegram group session had already ended at that point anyway. There are no meaningful changes to report—the system is stable. I'm checking the current status of the key sessions—the main cron is still running, the DTLX session ended at 22:55 UTC, and the Telegram session has restarted but isn't relevant to DTLX monitoring. Since there are no changes to report, I'll stay silent and update the heartbeat state instead. No change to report, but I should update the state file with the current timestamp and note the Telegram restart.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"Baseline (00:14 UTC) vs current (00:29 UTC):\\n\\n**Baseline running:** cron:ed2d0b5d ✅ cron:e7885813 ✅ cron:6f3323ef ✅ — same 3 crons still running  \\n**Baseline ended:** telegram:direct ended ~22:02 UTC — new instance of same session started ~00:22 UTC (same session type, natural restart cycle)  \\n**No failures. No new tasks. No blockers. Pipeline HEALTHY.**\\n\\n**Silent — nothing to report.**\"\n            }\n          ],\n          \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n          \"provider\": \"ahvholding\",\n          \"model\": \"AHV-Holding-DEV\",\n          \"usage\": {\n            \"input\": 427,\n            \"output\": 683,\n            \"totalTokens\": 45953,\n            \"cacheRead\": 14264,\n            \"cacheWrite\": 30579,\n            \"cost\": {\n              \"total\": 0\n            }\n          },\n          \"stopReason\": \"stop\",\n          \"timestamp\": 1776212977014,\n          \"responseId\": \"062e0ef22789d57fa38e950fdf339581\",\n          \"__openclaw\": {\n            \"id\": \"d3fe8a3f\",\n            \"seq\": 7\n          }\n        }\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"key\": \"agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134\",\n      \"kind\": \"other\",\n      \"channel\": \"telegram\",\n      \"origin\": {\n        \"provider\": \"telegram\",\n        \"accountId\": \"main_bot\"\n      },\n      \"displayName\": \"telegram:g-agent-master-orchestrator-telegram-direct-6053576134